TV-auc simulation

Ying Jin

1 Introduction

  • AUC and measures of discrimination are important model evaluation criteria for survival models.
  • Many estimators proposed, some work done examining the problem with violations of the PH assumption
  • No previous work identified critical flaw which affects reasonableness of these estimators’ use in prediction work
  • We are trying to identifying key flaw in common estimators of I/D AUC and their impact on Concordance
  • Proposal for which estimators to use in the future for prediction work

2 Method

2.1 Incidence/Dynamic AUC

For a fixed time point \(t > 0\) at various candidate thresholds of the biomarker \(\eta_i\). Specifically,
\[\begin{align*} \text{sensitivity}^{\mathbb{I}}(c,t) = & \text{TP}_t^{\mathbb{I}}(c) = \text{Pr}(\eta_i > c|T_i = t) \\ 1-\text{specificity}^{\mathbb{D}}(c,t) = & \text{FP}_t^{\mathbb{D}}(c) = 1-\text{Pr}(\eta_i \leq c|T_i > t) \\ \end{align*}\]

from which one can defined an incident/dynamic receiver operator characteristic (ROC) curve

\[\begin{align*} \text{ROC}_t^{\mathbb{I}/\mathbb{D}}(p) = \text{TP}_t^{\mathbb{I}}\{[\text{FP}_t^{\mathbb{D}}]^{-1}(p)\} \end{align*}\]

Consequently I/D AUC:

\[\begin{align*} \text{AUC}^{\mathbb{I}/\mathbb{D}}(t) &= \int_0^1 \text{ROC}_t^{\mathbb{I}/\mathbb{D}}(p)dp \end{align*}\]

2.1.1 Hagerty & Zhang estimator (semi-parametric)

From the Heagerty & Zhang paper, sensitivity and specificity is estimated based on cox PH model:

\[\begin{align*} \log \lambda_i(t) &= \log \lambda_0(t) + \bf{x}_i \bf{\beta} \\ &= \log \lambda_0(t) + \eta_i \\ \end{align*}\]

\[\hat{\text{TP}_t}^{\mathbb{I}}(c)=\frac{\sum_{k}I(\eta_k>c)I(T_k=t)exp(\eta_t)}{\sum_{j}I(T_j=t)exp(\eta_j)}\]

\[\text{FP}_t^{\mathbb{D}}(c) = \frac{\sum_{k}I(\eta_k>c)I(T_k>t)}{\sum_{j}I(T_j>t)}\]

ROC and \(AUC(t)\) estimated as the previous section by plugging in estimators of TP and FP. AUC is only evaluated as unique event time.

2.1.2 Fully non-parametric

\[\hat{\text{TP}_t}^{\mathbb{I}}(c) = \frac{\sum_{k}I(\eta_k>c)I(T_k=t)}{\sum_{j}I(T_j=t)}\] \[\hat{\text{FP}_t}^{\mathbb{D}}(c) = \frac{\sum_{k}I(\eta_k>c)I(T_k>t)}{\sum_{j}I(T_j>t)}\]

ROC(t), AUC(t) estimated using the same formula as previous sections

Since non-parametric AUC(t) is highly unstable, we can also smoothing it using regression splines.

2.2 Concordance

2.2.1 Integrating AUC(t)

\[\begin{align*} \text{C}^{\tau} &= \int_0^\tau\text{AUC}^{\mathbb{I}/\mathbb{D}}(t)w^{\tau(t)}dt \end{align*}\]

Where \(\tau\) is the end of follow-up period,

\[w^{\tau}(t) = 2f(t)S(t)/W^{\tau}\]

\[W^{\tau} =\int_0^\tau2f(t)S(t)dt =1-S^2(\tau)\] S(t) can be estimated from Kaplan-Meier curve. f(t) can be calculated using Trapezoidal rule over S(t) or smoothed S(t).

2.2.2 Gonen & Heller

\[C = \frac{2}{n(n-1)}\sum_{i<j}{\frac{I(\eta_j-\eta_i<0)}{1+exp(\eta_j-\eta_i)}+\frac{I(\eta_i-\eta_j<0)}{1+exp(\eta_i-\eta_j)}}\]

2.2.3 Harrel’s C-index

\[C = \frac{\sum_{i<j}I(T_i<T_j)I(\eta_i>\eta_j)I(\delta_i=1)+I(T_i>T_j)I(\eta_i<\eta_j)I(\delta_i=1)}{\sum_{i<j}I(T_i<T_j)I(\delta_i=1)+I(T_i>T_j)I(\delta_i=1)}\]

2.3 Simulation set up

  • 1000 iterations, sample size = 500
  • Signals \(X = (X_1, X_2, X_3)\), \(X_i \overset{i.i.d}{\sim} N(0, 1)\), \(\eta = \beta X\), \(\beta = (1, -1, 0.25)\)
  • Event time generated from Weibull baseline hazard
  • Censor time generated from exponential distribution, with maximum censor time \(\tau = 1\)
